SIMPLE: slender
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slender
<hw>Slen"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Slenderer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Slenderest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>slendre</ets>, <ets>sclendre</ets>, fr. OD. <ets>slinder</ets>
thin, slender, perhaps through a French form; cf. OD.
<ets>slinderen</ets>, <ets>slidderen</ets>, to creep; perh. akin to E.
<ets>slide</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Small or narrow in proportion
to the length or the height; not thick; slim; <as>as, a <ex>slender</ex>
stem or stalk of a plant</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>slender</xex>,
choleric man.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She, as a veil down to the <qex>slender</qex> waist,⟦br⟧
Her unadorned golden tresses wore.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Weak; feeble; not strong; slight; <as>as,
<ex>slender</ex> hope; a <ex>slender</ex> constitution</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mighty hearts are held in <qex>slender</qex> chains.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have inferred much from <qex>slender</qex> premises.</q>
<rj><qau>J. H. Newman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>slender</qex> utterance of the consonants.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Byrne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Moderate; trivial; inconsiderable; slight; <as>as, a
man of <ex>slender</ex> intelligence</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>slender</qex> degree of patience will enable him to enjoy
both the humor and the pathos.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Small; inadequate; meager; pitiful; <as>as,
<ex>slender</ex> means of support; a <ex>slender</ex>
pittance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Frequent begging makes <qex>slender</qex> alms.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Spare; abstemious; frugal; <as>as, a
<ex>slender</ex> diet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The good Ostorius often deigned⟦br⟧
To grace my <qex>slender</qex> table with his presence.</q>
<rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>Uttered with a thin tone; -- the
opposite of <xex>broad</xex>; <as>as, the <ex>slender</ex> vowels long
<ex>e</ex> and <ex>i</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Slen"der*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Slen"der*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slent</ent>⟦br⟧
